{{Infobox ancient site |name = Khallet el Hamra |native_name = |alternate_name = Khallet Hamra |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location = {{convert|1|km|mi}} southeast of [[Ain Ebel]], [[Lebanon]] |region = [[Nabatieh Governorate]] |coordinates = {{coord|33.1206|35.3008|display=inline}} |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Heavy Neolithic]], [[Acheulean]] |cultures = [[Qaraoun culture]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = [[Paul Bovier-Lapierre]], [[Henri Fleisch]] |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} [[File:Heavyneolithicscraper.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Heavy Neolithic tools of the Qaraoun culture found at Mtaileb I - Massive nosed scraper on a flake with irregular jagged edges, notches and "noses". Light grey and streaky silicious limestone.]] '''Khallet el Hamra''' or '''Khallet Hamra''' is a [[ravine]] or [[wadi]] joining the larger [[Wadi Yaroun]] located {{convert|1|km|mi}} southeast of [[Ain Ebel]]in the [[Bint Jbeil District]] of [[Nabatieh Governorate]] in [[Lebanon]].<ref name="CopelandWescombe1966">{{cite book|author1=L. Copeland|author2=P. Wescombe|title=Inventory of Stone-Age Sites in Lebanon: North, South and East-Central Lebanon, p. 40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qhPRQwAACAAJ|accessdate=3 March 2011|year=1966|publisher=Impr. Catholique}}</ref><ref>de Morgan, J., La préhistoire orientale, volume 3, p. 12, III, Paris, 1927.</ref>
A [[Heavy Neolithic]] archaeological site of the [[Qaraoun culture]] was discovered by [[jesuit]] [[archaeologist]] [[Paul Bovier-Lapierre]] in 1908. It was located to the south of a track that leads from Ain Ebel to [[Bint Jbeil]] at around {{convert|700|m|ft}} above sea level.<ref>Bovier-Lapierre, Paul., Stations préhistoriques du Beled Becharra (Hte Galilée), La Géographie, vol. 17, p. 77, 1908.</ref> Bovier-Lapierre considered several of the [[axe]]s found to be [[Chellean]] with one exceptionally large and finely made [[Acheulean]] chopper.<ref>Karge, P., Rephaim: Die Vorgeschichtliche Kultur Palästinas und Phöniziens, p. 43, Paderborn (First edition), 1917-1918.</ref> [[Henri Fleisch]] re-evaluated the materials in light of more modern studies and noted the finds to be only sparsely Acheulean with the [[assemblage (archaeology)|assemblage]] consisting of predominantly ''"abundant"'' Heavy Neolithic tools of the Qaraoun culture.<ref name="CopelandWescombe1966"/>
