[[File:A Country Genji by an Imitation Murasaki - Nise Murasaki inaka Genji.ehon.series.chapter..volume..cover.testscan.07.jpg|thumb|''Rustic Genji by a Fake Murasaki'', text by Ryūtei Tanehiko with illustrations by [[Utagawa Kunisada]]]]
[[File:Nisemurasaki Inaka Genji vol.12.jpg|thumbnail|Each volume has Part1's book and Part2's. The front covers of the two books show one picture.]]
{{nihongo|''Nise Murasaki inaka Genji''|偐紫田舎源氏}}, translated variously as ''The Rustic Genji'', ''False Murasaki and a Country Genji'', or ''A Fraudulent Murasaki's Bumpkin Genji'', is a late-[[Edo period]] [[Japanese literature|Japanese]] literary [[parody]] of the ''[[Tale of Genji]]'' by [[Murasaki Shikibu]].<ref name="Keene">{{cite book |title=World Within Walls: Japanese Literature of the Pre-Modern Era, 1600–1867 |author=[[Donald Keene|Keene, Donald]] |publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] |year=1999 |isbn=0231114672 |pages=429–435}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/gallery/yoshitoshi/works/P.16-2003_SE.html |title=False Murasaki and a Rural Genji (Nise murasaki inaka genji) |publisher=[[The Fitzwilliam Museum]] |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref><ref name="Shirane">{{cite book |title=Envisioning the Tale of Genji: Media, Gender, and Cultural Production |author=Haruo Shirane |publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] |year=2008 |isbn=9780231142373 |pages=211–239}}</ref> The work, by {{nihongo|Ryūtei Tanehiko|[[:ja:柳亭種彦|柳亭種彦]]}} (1783–1842) with illustrations by [[Utagawa Kunisada]], was published in a [[Woodblock printing in Japan|woodblock]] edition between 1829 and 1842 by Senkakudō.<ref name="Shirane"/> 

The parody shifts the time-frame from the [[Heian period]] to the [[Muromachi period]],<ref name=uematsu>{{cite book|last=Uematsu|first=Yasushi (植松安 1885–1945)|title=Kokubungaku gaisetsu (国文学史概説)|publisher=Kōbundō(広文堂)|year=1928|format=National Diet Library|url=http://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/1120146|pages=280–282}}</ref> and replaces inserted [[Waka (poetry)|waka]] poetry with [[haiku]].<ref name=uematsu/>

It was the best-selling example of the genre known as {{nihongo|''gōkan''|[[:ja:合巻|合巻]]}}, a popular literary form that merged image with text.<ref name="Shirane"/> The plot centres on the outlandish adventures of Ashikaga Mitsuuji, second son of [[Ashikaga Yoshimasa]], while seeking to recover a stolen sword, mirror, and poem, upon which the security of the realm depend.<ref name="Shirane"/> The preface to the first chapter introduces the character Ōfuji, whose nickname is Murasaki Shikibu.<ref name="Shirane"/> In the preface to the tenth chapter, Tanehiko describes his own literary project:<ref name="Keene"/> <blockquote>When I first began to write ''The Rustic Genji'' an aged friend said to me: "You should try to the best of your ability to preserve the language of the original and not alter the story. It will probably then be of some use to young people who haven't read ''The Tale of Genji''." But a young friend said, "You should vary the plot. Weave in effects from [[Kabuki]] and the [[bunraku|puppet theatre]]. Surely there can't be anyone who hasn't read ''Genji''."</blockquote>

